#compdef pushpin
# =============================================================================
# pushpin — Fastly's "A proxy server for adding push to your API,
#           used at the core of Fastly's Fanout service" — a Rust
#           reverse proxy that adds long-poll + HTTP streaming +
#           WebSocket-over-HTTP push capabilities to existing HTTP
#           APIs WITHOUT modifying the backend service.  Pushpin
#           sits in front of a normal HTTP backend and transparently
#           upgrades certain responses to long-lived streaming
#           connections.  Distinguishing from Nginx push module +
#           Centrifugo + Faye + socket.io + Pusher + Ably + Soketi
#           by:
#             - GRIP PROTOCOL — Generic Realtime Intermediary
#               Protocol; the backend instructs Pushpin (via HTTP
#               headers) to hold a connection open + listen on
#               named channels for push messages
#             - PROTOCOL-AGNOSTIC — pushes the SAME messages over
#               HTTP long-poll OR HTTP streaming OR Server-Sent
#               Events OR WebSocket-over-HTTP, transparent to the
#               backend
#             - FASTLY PRODUCTION-PROVEN — powers Fastly's Fanout
#               service handling millions of concurrent realtime
#               connections in production
#             - MULTIPLE BINARIES IN ONE WORKSPACE: pushpin (main)
#               + pushpin-connmgr (connection manager) + pushpin-
#               handler (request handler) + pushpin-proxy (proxy
#               layer) + pushpin-publish (message publisher) +
#               m2adapter (Mongrel2 adapter) + pushpin-legacy
#               (legacy entry point)
#             - LAYERED CONFIGURATION via config-rs: TOML config
#               file + CLI overrides + environment-variable
#               overrides + sane defaults, with hierarchical
#               merging
#             - ROUTE FILE + INLINE --route OVERRIDES — backend
#               URL routing configured in routes file; CLI --route
#               flag (repeatable) overrides per-instance
#             - INSTANCE ID via --id for running multiple
#               independent Pushpin processes on the same machine
#             - 5-LEVEL LOG VERBOSITY: --loglevel 0 (Error) / 1
#               (Warn) / 2 (Info, default) / 3 (Debug) / 4+
#               (Trace); --verbose shortcut for --loglevel=3
#           Used by: realtime API providers, Fastly Fanout
#           customers, GRIP-protocol-aware backends, and anyone
#           needing to add long-poll / streaming / WebSocket
#           capabilities to a standard HTTP service without
#           rewriting it.
#
# Author:  Fastly, Inc. (acquired Pushpin from Fanout in 2018).
#          Originally by Justin Karneges at Fanout; continues
#          development under Fastly's open-source program.
#          Migrating from C++ to Rust since 2023.  License:
#          Apache-2.0.
# Source:  https://github.com/fastly/pushpin
#          https://github.com/fastly/pushpin/blob/main/src/bin/pushpin.rs
#          https://github.com/fastly/pushpin/blob/main/src/runner/mod.rs
#          https://pushpin.org (project home + docs)
# CLI:     src/bin/pushpin.rs + src/runner/mod.rs — uses clap 4.x
#          derive (`#[derive(Parser)]`) with 7 named flags + no
#          positional arguments.  Headline library: **config-rs**
#          (clap is well-documented across many Rust completions;
#          config-rs is the new variant being documented here,
#          opening Axis 13).
# Library: config-rs (https://github.com/mehcode/config-rs)
#          ("config-rs" — Ryan Leckey (mehcode on GitHub) —
#           released 2017 as a "Layered configuration system for
#           Rust applications (with strong support for 12-factor
#           applications)".  Distinct from every previously-
#           documented Rust library by being narrowly focused on
#           HIERARCHICAL CONFIGURATION FILE LOADING + ENV-VAR
#           OVERRIDE MERGING for production-grade application
#           configuration:
#             1. 7 BUILT-IN FILE FORMAT BACKENDS via feature
#                flags:
#                  - TOML (default, via toml crate)
#                  - YAML (via yaml-rust2)
#                  - JSON (via serde_json)
#                  - JSON5 (via json5)
#                  - INI (via rust-ini)
#                  - RON (via ron)
#                  - All-in-one Config::builder() picks based
#                    on file extension
#             2. SOURCE LAYERING via ConfigBuilder — sources
#                are added in order of decreasing priority:
#                  Config::builder()
#                      .add_source(File::with_name("default"))
#                      .add_source(File::with_name(&env_config).required(false))
#                      .add_source(Environment::with_prefix("APP"))
#                      .build()
#                Later sources OVERRIDE earlier ones — supports
#                the 12-factor pattern of base config + env-
#                specific overrides + env-var overrides
#             3. ENVIRONMENT::with_prefix() — Environment source
#                automatically maps env-vars to config keys:
#                  APP__DATABASE__URL → config["database"]["url"]
#                  APP__SERVER__PORT → config["server"]["port"]
#                Default separator is "__" but configurable;
#                useful for 12-factor configuration via Docker/
#                Kubernetes env vars
#             4. SERDE INTEGRATION — config.try_deserialize::<MyConfig>()
#                deserializes the layered config into a typed
#                struct via serde; type-safe access throughout
#                the program
#             5. WATCHED FILE RELOADING via the file source's
#                refresh_rate option — config can hot-reload
#                when its underlying file changes
#             6. RYAN-LECKEY (MEHCODE) PROVENANCE — Ryan also
#                maintains sqlx (the dominant async Rust SQL
#                library) — config-rs is part of his "production-
#                grade Rust infrastructure" library family
#             7. 12-FACTOR APP COMPLIANT — designed explicitly
#                for the 12-factor methodology: config from
#                files + env vars + sensible defaults, with
#                env-var precedence)
# License: Apache-2.0 (pushpin); MIT OR Apache-2.0 (config-rs)
# Status:  pushpin — 3,847+ stars on fastly/pushpin, production-
#          deployed by Fastly Fanout; config-rs — 3,163+ stars
